                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think the critical part for charming is what to do when charm breaks. With a 990 hitting pet on your ass you don't have time to sit down, figure out a strategy and mem spells <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /> So PLAN how to handle a break in advance, mem the necessary spells and MAKE HOTKEYS. Hotkeys are faster than clicky clicky, and with a mad pet coming for you time is limited.
<br />

<br />
There seems to be 3 strategies for handling a broken charm:
<br />
1. Run for your life!
<br />
When charm breaks be on max range already, or run away out to max range. Then recharm before pet hits you. Might need some fast cast focus, depending on what charm spell you use and any range focus. This is fairly mana efficient and usually fairly fast as you dont have to wait for root/mez to go off. Needs a bit of room though. Can use root/mez first instead of direct charm, which sort if is a variation of strategy 2.
<br />

<br />
2. Calm down!
<br />
Mez or root pet when it breaks. Then re-debuff and charm. Wastes a bit of time as you might have to wait a bit for pet to be ready to go. 
<br />

<br />
3. The great gamble!
<br />
Channel a stun or WoM, then recharm before it wears off. Or just channel the charm  <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="icon_razz.gif" border="0" /> . This means pet WILL get a few hits on you, so might work best if you have some sort of healer. Probably the fastest way of recharming. I always use this when grouped.
<br />

<br />
There are variations of these, know your tools and use as situation demands. You should be proficient in all 3 and use whichever suits the situation, group and gear best.
<br />

<br />
The important thing is to know what to do <span style="font-weight: bold">before</span> charm breaks, and have hotkeys ready(and know where those keys are so you can do it blindly, no time for fumbling).</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
