                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
If using a pet to kill a named (i.e. BoT elementals), I will always slow my pet and keep it slowed until we get to the named. I invis to break charm, re-Tash, and then recharm. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Oh, dear god no!!!! Please tell me we didn't have an enchanter actually recommend slowing a pet <img src="images/smiles/icon_eek.gif" alt="icon_eek.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
I've seen some reasonable arguments for not hasting a pet, although I strongly disagree with them, but actually slowing it? Even if you are not at the mob you are wanting to fight it should be hasted to get you there quicker.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
They I cast haste to overwrite the charm (I use Anya's Quickening for charmed pets). 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I assume this is a typo, haste doesn't overwrite charm, I'm assuming you meant cast haste to overwrite slow. Haste (any haste) does not overwrite slow (any slow). They stack to a degree. If you slow your mob 70% and then haste it 68% it's a hasted/slowed mob. This is why when you group and a tank cries they got slowed, you don't rehaste them. They are all ready hasted, you wait for slow to wear off or have the healer cure them.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
I always stay in the corner if possible when using charmed pet because it it gets loose, I have a better chance to channel Word of Morrel. WoM - CoD has always worked for me. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Very good advice. The only thing I would change is that if it's a big enough room and you know the spawn cylce (you've been pulling it) your better of standing at range in the middle of the room than close and in a corner. Better to land the charm before it touches you than trying to channel through a pounding. Of course the best solution is to be in a corner AND at range in case you fizzle or interrupt so you can try again. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Don't try to take on summoning mobs with Charmed pet (i.e. Militis, not good at all) or you will die 75% of the time on a charm break.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Solo or in a group? In a group, don't worry about it... you be ready to recharm your pet and let the MA worry about it summoning. Don't Charm mobs that summon if it can be avoided. Attack tehm as much as you like. If you are solo, you should use some caution, but kill those summoners! Make sure your pet is hasted and nuke hard once your pet has done significant damage. Your only goal is to make sure it dies before charm breaks, but assuming TD3, Tash and (debateable) high charisma, you should maintain charm most of the time. [/quote]</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
